message.content: Lupinus nanus, commonly known as dwarf lupine, is a species of flowering plant in the pea family, Fabaceae. The plant is characterized by its short stature, reaching only 30-45 cm in height. The leaves are alternate and palmately compound, with 5-7 leaflets. The flowers of Lupinus nanus are arranged in dense, erect spikes, and come in a range of colors, including pink, blue, purple, and white. The plant prefers well-drained soils and is often found in open, rocky or sandy areas, as well as disturbed habitats such as roadsides and fields. A common garden plant, Lupinus nanus is often used as a decorative addition to flower beds and borders. Its visual characteristics include bright and showy flowers, a short and compact stature, and palmately compound leaves.
